      "body" : "@Josh :shrug: That sounds more like an issue with the queue consumer; if it doesn’t have a way to throttle itself and/or it isn’t callback-/promise-driven there’s already a potential problem. But this is orthogonal to the question, and my comment. Busy loops in JS are a problem because they have direct impact on system behavior. Are there isolated cases where they’re ok(-ish)? Sure."
    }, {
      "owner" : {
        "account_id" : 311746,
        "reputation" : 416,
        "user_id" : 625488,
        "user_type" : "registered",
        "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/940208cf6b8a743568eaf7c9d51412d0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
        "display_name" : "user625488",
        "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/625488/user625488"
      },
      "edited" : false,
      "score" : 0,
      "creation_date" : 1699878790,
      "post_id" : 16077558,
      "comment_id" : 136582185,
      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "In JavaScript, all stuff that gets executed gets executed (in theory) on a single thread. Sitting and looping while doing nothing until enough time passes blocks the event loop. <code>Thread.sleep()</code> in Java doesn&#39;t block other threads from executing, while it sort of has the effect of preventing anything else from executing in JavaScript. Which is why the solution proposed by this answer is neither useful, in most situations, nor advisable. You expect something to happen, while you sleep, and it won&#39;t."
    } ],
